41
00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:32.160
The NCI's Human Tumor Atlas Network program is a collaborative

42
00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:35.800
initiative to map the tumor evolution at a single-cell resolution.

43
00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:39.700
It aims to build highly dynamic three-dimensional

44
00:02:40.740 --> 00:02:44.640
atlases of pre-cancer and tumor. The main goals include the

45
00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.480
integration of molecular, cellular, and tumor tissue composition and

46
00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:52.440
architecture involving the tumor microenvironment and immune milieu,

47
00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:54.760
describe the transition across

48
00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:59.460
the cancer spectrum, premalignant lesions to malignancy,

49
00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.560
locally invasive to metastatic cancer,

50
00:03:02.760 --> 00:03:04.640
responsive to resistant cancer type,

51
00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:09.400
with the ultimate goal of enabling predictive modeling to refine detection and

52
00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:10.680
therapeutic choices.

53
00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:16.660
HTAN program was funded under two cycles, under Phase I,

54
00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:19.460
which was from 2018 to 2024.

55
00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:23.100
It encompasses various tumor types.

56
00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:27.340
Six of them are listed here: lung, pancreas, colon, breast, skin, and

57
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:28.040
pediatric.

58
00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:33.620
The highlights from the HTAN Phase I is published in a collection

59
00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:37.370
