160
00:09:50.392 --> 00:09:53.532
So my name is Hunter Shane, and I am one of the

161
00:09:53.552 --> 00:09:57.032
co-PIs of one of the phase two atlases, the

162
00:09:57.492 --> 00:10:01.272
precancer atlas of skin cancer. And I'm thrilled to also

163
00:10:01.352 --> 00:10:03.672
chair this session and kick off the scientific

164
00:10:04.452 --> 00:10:08.372
talks for today's session. So I will walk you

165
00:10:08.432 --> 00:10:12.412
through the journey from a normal type of skin cell known as a

166
00:10:12.452 --> 00:10:16.432
keratinocyte, to a common form of skin cancer known as cutaneous

167
00:10:16.442 --> 00:10:17.612
squamous cell carcinoma.

168
00:10:19.392 --> 00:10:23.372
These are my disclosures. And if you want to understand the evolution

169
00:10:23.492 --> 00:10:27.092
of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, you need to first start by

170
00:10:27.172 --> 00:10:30.312
understanding what are the somatic alterations in normal skin cells.

171
00:10:30.812 --> 00:10:33.682
And I'll pose the thought experiment to the audience, and that's how might you do

172
00:10:33.712 --> 00:10:37.452
that. Your reflexive reaction is probably to just sequence normal

173
00:10:37.472 --> 00:10:41.062
skin, and this is not a bad idea. But the problem with this

174
00:10:41.092 --> 00:10:44.992
approach is that it gives you an average signal from the complex mixture

175
00:10:45.052 --> 00:10:48.952
of cells that are there. Now, to be sure, this has been used to great success

176
00:10:48.992 --> 00:10:52.832
in the past. You can go all the way back to 1994 when Doug Brash's

177
00:10:52.892 --> 00:10:56.412
group used this approach to show that there are p53

178
00:10:56.452 --> 00:10:59.552
mutant patches of keratinocytes in normal human skin.

179
00:10:59.972 --> 00:11:03.572
And then, of course, Inigo Martin-Carrena and colleagues really turbocharged this

180
00:11:03.632 --> 00:11:07.312
approach in 2015 in a landmark paper, to show more

181
00:11:07.372 --> 00:11:11.112
generally the mutational landscape of clonally related patches of

182
00:11:11.132 --> 00:11:13.232
keratinocytes in human skin.

183
00:11:14.112 --> 00:11:17.892
But I would argue the ideal

184
00:11:18.032 --> 00:11:20.672
resolution to do this would be at single-cell resolution.

185
00:11:21.752 --> 00:11:25.512
In my opinion, single-cell DNA sequencing technologies have come a

186
00:11:25.572 --> 00:11:28.912
long way, but they still suffer from low levels of sensitivity and

187
00:11:28.952 --> 00:11:30.832
specificity in their mutation calls.

188
00:11:31.452 --> 00:11:34.352
And so to get around this challenge, our laboratory developed the following

189
00:11:34.432 --> 00:11:38.192
workflow, where we start out by extracting a bulk population of skin cells,

190
00:11:38.652 --> 00:11:42.092
and then we single-cell sort them so that there is now one cell per well in a

191
00:11:42.232 --> 00:11:45.912
96-well plate. We clonally expand these cells as much as possible.

192
00:11:46.452 --> 00:11:50.322
These are cells from normal tissue, so they have a limited replicative ability.

193
00:11:51.592 --> 00:11:55.221
But it is easier to genotype from a starting point of, let's say, 100 cells than

194
00:11:55.292 --> 00:11:58.932
one cell. But to finish the job, we would lyse these small colonies of

195
00:11:58.992 --> 00:12:02.732
cells, releasing their genomic DNA and mRNA, and then

196
00:12:02.792 --> 00:12:05.632
further amplify these nucleic acid populations in

197
00:12:05.712 --> 00:12:09.200
vitro.And between the combination of ex vivo clonal

198
00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:12.670
expansion, in vitro nucleic acid amplification,

199
00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:17.140
and a heavy dose of bioinformatics that I'm not going to go into, we are able to

200
00:12:17.180 --> 00:12:20.820
call somatic alterations in individual skin cells at nearly

201
00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.580
100% sensitivity and specificity.

202
00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:28.460
I think the value of this data is best exemplified with an example.

203
00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:31.680
And shown here is a skin biopsy that measures three

204
00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:35.470
millimeters in diameter. I hope you can appreciate

205
00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:39.149
that for all intents and purposes, this is physiologically normal human skin.

206
00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.040
It came from the back of a 75-year-old woman.

207
00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:45.630
She did have a previous history of skin cancer, as well as

208
00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:48.730
self-reported high levels of cumulative UV exposure.

209
00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:53.440
But this is normal skin from which we genotype 10 individual

210
00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:57.520
keratinocytes. And the first thing I want to point out to you is that

211
00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:01.540
many of these so-called normal keratinocytes actually have mutations

212
00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:04.620
known to drive keratinocyte carcinogenesis.

213
00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:08.440
This trio of cells has a biallelic loss of function NOTCH1

214
00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:11.780
mutations, as well as loss of function mutations affecting

215
00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:14.920
p53, FAT1, PBRM1,

216
00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:19.400
NOTCH2. And then two of these cells further acquired yet

217
00:13:19.420 --> 00:13:23.220
another NOTCH1 mutation. And then one of these cells acquired yet

218
00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:26.780
another NOTCH2 mutation. And so if you're keeping count,

219
00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:31.200
these cells have up to eight pathogenic mutations in the same

220
00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:31.560
cell.

221
00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:36.300
Now, if you had done bulk cell sequencing, you might have gotten lucky and detected

222
00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:39.360
some of these mutations, but you would have never recognized that they were

223
00:13:39.420 --> 00:13:41.220
co-occurring within the same cell.

224
00:13:42.220 --> 00:13:45.640
Cancer is thought to arise after the accumulation of four to five pathogenic

225
00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:49.360
mutations, and so we were somewhat surprised that these cells can

226
00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:53.280
tolerate up to eight driver mutations, and yet that is insufficient

227
00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:55.160
to form a discernible neoplasm.

228
00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:59.620
Now, the second thing I want to point out is that many of these cells are

229
00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:03.470
clonally related. I cannot say with any degree of certainty how

230
00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:07.380
these clonally related cells are spatially organized, but we have drawn

231
00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:10.900
a schematic here of how they may have theoretically been organized.

232
00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:15.270
And this is drawn to scale if you assume that the size of each clonally related

233
00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:19.120
patch of keratinocytes is proportional to the number of cells within it.

234
00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:23.470
A couple things to point out here. It's perhaps not surprising that the cells with

235
00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:27.460
pathogenic mutations have formed a patch, but you'll see that there are also

236
00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.080
these two patches of keratinocytes without any apparent

237
00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:35.100
pathogenic mutations. And not only that, they are of a similar size,

238
00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:37.879
and I'll circle back to that point in a couple of slides.

239
00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:42.320
Now, the last thing I want to point out to you is the extraordinary range of

240
00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:46.110
mutation burdens of these cells. And you might not have initially recognized this

241
00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:50.040
because I had to introduce a break in the y-axis in order to plot all this data

242
00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:53.040
on the same graph. But these three cells with pathogenic

243
00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:56.740
mutations have 40 times as many mutations as their neighboring

244
00:14:56.840 --> 00:15:00.460
cells without pathogenic mutations. So what's going on here?

245
00:15:01.620 --> 00:15:04.590
What's shown here is more generally the landscape of somatic alterations from

246
00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:08.460
individual keratinocytes. And exactly as I showed you in the previous slide,

247
00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:13.100
somewhat paradoxically, most keratinocytes actually have somewhat low

248
00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:16.940
mutation burdens with relatively low proportions of

249
00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.720
UV radiation-induced DNA damage.

250
00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:23.360
But there's this tail of keratinocytes with extraordinarily high mutation

251
00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:27.200
burdens. And when you ask what's notable about them, every single one of

252
00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:31.240
these has an underlying pathogenic mutation, typically in the p53

253
00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:33.060
or Notch signaling pathway.

254
00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:37.620
So this is another example where had you done bulk sequencing, you would have

255
00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:41.580
correctly deduced that the average mutation burden per cell is

256
00:15:41.620 --> 00:15:44.920
around five mutations per megabase, but you would have missed the fact

257
00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:48.880
that this is actually a mixture of cells with one mutation

258
00:15:49.100 --> 00:15:52.840
per megabase and some with up to 50 mutations per megabase.

259
00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:57.540
Now, this is a classic example of a mutator phenotype, meaning that

260
00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:01.540
these p53 and Notch pathway mutations are causing those cells to accumulate

261
00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:03.700
mutations more rapidly than their neighboring cells.

262
00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:07.940
But are they doing something else, such as inducing a proliferative advantage?

263
00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:12.980
And I'm not so sure that they are. So shown here is the inferred surface

264
00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:16.960
area of each clonally related patch of keratinocytes that we could detect in the

265
00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:20.960
study. And you'll see here in red, some have pathogenic

266
00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:23.160
mutations, but actually most of them don't.

267
00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:27.520
And the ones with pathogenic mutations do not appear to be any larger

268
00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:29.500
than those without pathogenic mutations.

269
00:16:30.300 --> 00:16:33.880
You can go back to the Martin Krainak paper, and they too noticed with a completely

270
00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:37.900
different technology that clones carrying driver mutations do not appear to

271
00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:39.700
be much larger than those without them.

272
00:16:40.520 --> 00:16:42.700
So I'd be curious to hear anyone's take on this, but my take

273
00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:47.680
is that these p53 and Notch mutations are conferring a persistence

274
00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:51.330
advantage, but not necessarily a strong proliferative advantage,

275
00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:55.780
meaning that when a keratinocyte has one of these mutations, it is less likely

276
00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:59.580
to undergo apoptosis in the face of high levels of UV radiation-induced

277
00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:02.940
DNA damage, and that causes them to accumulate mutations more

278
00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:06.530
rapidly. Maybe they'll passively expand in

279
00:17:06.580 --> 00:17:10.020
the space occupied by neighboring cells that do die out, but they don't really have

280
00:17:10.040 --> 00:17:13.560
a strong proliferative advantage relative to those other cells.

281
00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:18.780
So I've brought you up to this point, what I like to call the pre-neoplastic phases

282
00:17:18.860 --> 00:17:22.661
of progression. What follows next is the premalignant phase of progression,

283
00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:26.921
and in the setting of skin, this is a benign neoplasm known as an

284
00:17:26.980 --> 00:17:28.100
actinic keratosis.

285
00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:32.740
And in rare cases, an actinic keratosis can further progress

286
00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:34.980
into a cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.

287
00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:39.840
And so in order to better understand these phases of progression, we assembled a

288
00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:43.800
cohort of informative cases where we could identify a cutaneous

289
00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:47.760
squamous cell carcinoma at that moment in which it was ostensibly growing out of a

290
00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:50.420
preexisting and still intact precancerous

291
00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:53.560
neoplasm, such as this actinic keratosis shown

292
00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:57.460
here. We would microdissect and sequence each region, allowing us to infer

293
00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:00.440
the order in which somatic alterations accumulated.

294
00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:03.630
And much to our surprise, more often than not, these

295
00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:06.230
neoplasms were not phylogenetically related.

296
00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:10.568
So that's indicated in the scatter plot.You can see that there's these mutations

297
00:18:10.668 --> 00:18:14.228
hugging the X-axis here. These are exclusive to the actinic

298
00:18:14.268 --> 00:18:17.948
keratosis region. And then you'll see these mutations hugging the Y-axis.

299
00:18:18.008 --> 00:18:20.408
These are exclusive to the squamous cell carcinoma.

300
00:18:21.188 --> 00:18:24.848
If these were related, we would have seen some mutations in the middle here with

301
00:18:24.868 --> 00:18:28.748
high allele frequencies in both the actinic keratosis and the squamous cell

302
00:18:28.768 --> 00:18:29.308
carcinoma.

303
00:18:30.268 --> 00:18:31.568
So this is what we call a collision.

304
00:18:31.608 --> 00:18:35.128
These are just two neoplasms that just so happen to be near each other, but they

305
00:18:35.168 --> 00:18:39.118
are not genetically related. But we scraped and scratched and

306
00:18:39.168 --> 00:18:42.657
clawed and spent a lot of money on uninformative neoplasms,

307
00:18:43.168 --> 00:18:46.188
but eventually we started to find a handful of cutaneous squamous cell

308
00:18:46.208 --> 00:18:49.968
carcinomas that did actually evolve from the adjacent

309
00:18:50.168 --> 00:18:53.868
actinic keratosis. When these two neoplasms are next to one another,

310
00:18:54.468 --> 00:18:57.388
it's only about 10% of the time that they are actually related.

311
00:18:57.938 --> 00:19:01.928
And this is one of those examples where you can see here clearly that there

312
00:19:01.938 --> 00:19:05.928
are mutations with high allele frequencies shared between both the actinic

313
00:19:05.948 --> 00:19:08.708
keratosis and the cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma,

314
00:19:09.588 --> 00:19:13.228
as well as some mutations that are exclusive to the cutaneous squamous cell

315
00:19:13.267 --> 00:19:17.228
carcinoma. So you can draw a phylogenetic tree based on this distribution of

316
00:19:17.248 --> 00:19:20.668
shared and unshared mutations to deduce the order in which they

317
00:19:20.688 --> 00:19:21.348
accumulated.

318
00:19:22.308 --> 00:19:25.728
And here the actinic keratosis is driven by loss of function

319
00:19:25.968 --> 00:19:29.868
NOTCH1 and 2 mutations, as well as a loss of function

320
00:19:29.948 --> 00:19:33.068
p53 mutation. This is not necessarily surprising.

321
00:19:33.668 --> 00:19:36.888
We know these mutations are common in normal skin, and they would, of course,

322
00:19:37.588 --> 00:19:40.948
likely be inherited in actinic keratosis that grow out of them.

323
00:19:41.908 --> 00:19:45.528
But we also saw a TERT promoter mutation and a loss of function CDKN2A

324
00:19:45.588 --> 00:19:49.398
alteration. These are not so common in normal skin and

325
00:19:49.488 --> 00:19:52.908
probably are responsible for the formation of a discernible

326
00:19:53.008 --> 00:19:56.528
neoplasm. As for what drove the transition to cutaneous squamous cell

327
00:19:56.568 --> 00:20:00.418
carcinoma, that appears in this case to be driven by a loss of

328
00:20:00.468 --> 00:20:01.768
function ARID2 mutation,

329
00:20:02.648 --> 00:20:05.448
as well as a hotspot mutation affecting the SIBL oncogene.

330
00:20:06.048 --> 00:20:09.928
This is a well-established RASopathy mutation, meaning that it is known

331
00:20:09.968 --> 00:20:13.348
to activate the RTK RAS MAPK kinase signaling cascade.

332
00:20:14.248 --> 00:20:18.128
So that was just one case, but if you look more broadly across all the

333
00:20:18.148 --> 00:20:21.668
bonafide cases of cutaneous squamous cell carcinomas that we could identify

334
00:20:22.328 --> 00:20:26.288
that did evolve from a neighboring actinic keratosis, these patterns largely

335
00:20:26.328 --> 00:20:26.767
held up.

336
00:20:27.568 --> 00:20:31.538
p53 and Notch pathway mutations occur early and often and are

337
00:20:31.568 --> 00:20:33.168
present at all stages of neoplasia.

338
00:20:35.088 --> 00:20:38.248
TERT promoter mutations and mutations that disable the G1S checkpoint,

339
00:20:38.648 --> 00:20:42.208
typically loss of function CDKN2A mutations, these seem to

340
00:20:42.248 --> 00:20:46.198
emerge in actinic keratosis and are retained in cutaneous

341
00:20:46.198 --> 00:20:49.128
squamous cell carcinoma. And then this is not obligate.

342
00:20:49.968 --> 00:20:53.908
Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma does not have to have a MAP kinase pathway

343
00:20:53.988 --> 00:20:56.888
mutation or a loss of function SWI/SNF mutation.

344
00:20:57.288 --> 00:21:01.188
But when they occur, these most often mark the transition to

345
00:21:01.288 --> 00:21:02.827
cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.

346
00:21:04.388 --> 00:21:08.248
Now, because it was so difficult to find these informative cases, as part of HTAN,

347
00:21:08.308 --> 00:21:11.408
we're now layering on multi-omic assays whenever we do.

348
00:21:11.418 --> 00:21:14.448
And this is one example where we've done spatial transcriptomics

349
00:21:14.888 --> 00:21:18.508
on a case where we know that the cancer was

350
00:21:18.528 --> 00:21:20.378
phylogenetically related to the pre-cancer.

351
00:21:20.888 --> 00:21:24.288
And I thought this was an interesting example because you can see here in

352
00:21:24.308 --> 00:21:28.048
blue, there's this band of immune infiltrate that's beneath both the

353
00:21:28.068 --> 00:21:31.728
cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma and the actinic keratosis.

354
00:21:32.508 --> 00:21:35.608
But these immune cells could not be in more different states.

355
00:21:36.368 --> 00:21:40.297
As you can see here, the cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma cells are expressing

356
00:21:40.328 --> 00:21:44.308
high levels of checkpoint ligands, and concomitantly, the lymphocytes

357
00:21:44.348 --> 00:21:47.998
in their vicinity are expressing high levels of checkpoints,

358
00:21:48.888 --> 00:21:52.108
whereas there's not much activity in the immune

359
00:21:53.188 --> 00:21:55.898
cells and the actinic keratosis cells above them.

360
00:21:56.668 --> 00:22:00.498
And so this suggests that one major tumor microenvironmental change that

361
00:22:00.528 --> 00:22:04.248
marks the transition to malignancy is the engagement of

362
00:22:04.268 --> 00:22:08.238
immune checkpoints. And our hope is that as we sequence more of these cases,

363
00:22:08.308 --> 00:22:11.588
we can begin to connect these microenvironmental changes to

364
00:22:12.168 --> 00:22:15.088
pathogenic mutations that coincide with them.

365
00:22:16.848 --> 00:22:20.268
So I've brought you up to this point from the evolution of a normal skin cell to a

366
00:22:20.308 --> 00:22:24.218
primary cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, but these neoplasms are

367
00:22:24.248 --> 00:22:28.138
not done evolving. Approximately 3% of patients who have a

368
00:22:28.138 --> 00:22:32.008
primary cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma will eventually develop

369
00:22:32.048 --> 00:22:35.408
metastatic disease. And I think you can look at this number from two different

370
00:22:35.448 --> 00:22:39.148
perspectives. On the one hand, this is a relatively good

371
00:22:39.168 --> 00:22:42.408
prognosis compared to many other cancer subtypes.

372
00:22:42.448 --> 00:22:45.688
On the other hand, this still leads to a lot of sleepless nights where patients are

373
00:22:45.708 --> 00:22:49.648
left wondering how aggressively should they treat their tumor in order to

374
00:22:49.688 --> 00:22:52.997
avoid being in that 3% who will eventually develop metastatic

375
00:22:53.068 --> 00:22:56.628
disease. And regrettably, we do not have high-quality

376
00:22:56.688 --> 00:23:00.108
biomarkers to predict who will progress to metastatic disease.

377
00:23:01.288 --> 00:23:04.908
And so to address this gap in knowledge, I began a collaboration with a

378
00:23:04.948 --> 00:23:07.758
wonderful group from Erasmus University and

379
00:23:07.848 --> 00:23:09.668
SkylineDX in Europe.

380
00:23:10.788 --> 00:23:13.168
They had assembled what is called the DeSquam study.

381
00:23:13.548 --> 00:23:17.528
This is a nationwide cohort of nearly 45,000 primary cutaneous squamous cell

382
00:23:17.568 --> 00:23:20.728
carcinomas with detailed clinical and histopathologic

383
00:23:20.768 --> 00:23:24.738
information, as well as outcome. And if you study another cancer,

384
00:23:24.828 --> 00:23:28.418
maybe this doesn't impress you, but in the United States, we made the regrettable

385
00:23:28.508 --> 00:23:32.028
decision to not include cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma in our SEER cancer

386
00:23:32.088 --> 00:23:35.928
registry. And so I don't even think this study could have been done exclusively in

387
00:23:35.948 --> 00:23:36.508
this country.

388
00:23:37.348 --> 00:23:40.768
And we took a subset of these cases for molecular analyses.

389
00:23:41.448 --> 00:23:45.368
We constructed this as a nested case control study where half of the

390
00:23:45.388 --> 00:23:48.908
tumors or cases defined as primary cutaneous squamous cell

391
00:23:48.928 --> 00:23:52.568
carcinomas that over the next 10 years eventually

392
00:23:52.608 --> 00:23:56.548
progressed to metastatic disease and half were controls, meaning that they did not

393
00:23:56.568 --> 00:24:00.348
progress to metastatic disease. And we made sure that the controls were matched for

394
00:24:00.388 --> 00:24:04.368
clinical and histopathologic risk factors, thereby ensuring that if we do

395
00:24:04.468 --> 00:24:08.428
see molecular differences, they are likely to be prognostic above and

396
00:24:08.488 --> 00:24:09.948
beyond common staging systems.

397
00:24:10.768 --> 00:24:14.428
We performed whole exome sequencing and whole transcriptomic sequencing on these

398
00:24:14.468 --> 00:24:18.404
tumors.Now, the first thing we did is we established the landscape of driver

399
00:24:18.464 --> 00:24:22.084
mutations in cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.

400
00:24:22.464 --> 00:24:26.404
Another regrettable decision was the Cancer Genome Atlas project did not include

401
00:24:26.424 --> 00:24:30.094
cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma among its cancers that were

402
00:24:30.124 --> 00:24:30.604
profiled.

403
00:24:31.464 --> 00:24:34.684
Also, cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma has an extraordinarily high mutation

404
00:24:34.784 --> 00:24:38.654
burden, which makes it difficult to recognize driver mutations amidst the numerous

405
00:24:38.764 --> 00:24:40.744
passenger mutations within each tumor.

406
00:24:41.184 --> 00:24:44.564
And so our field had not yet even settled on a consensus set of driver

407
00:24:44.604 --> 00:24:47.844
mutations. So this is now the largest analysis available.

408
00:24:48.744 --> 00:24:52.704
We used Intogen to identify genes under selection and propose

409
00:24:52.764 --> 00:24:56.584
here this list of approximately 40 genes, which we

410
00:24:56.604 --> 00:24:59.204
believe are the main drivers of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.

411
00:25:00.144 --> 00:25:03.964
But the main advantage of our cohort is that we have metastatic

412
00:25:04.034 --> 00:25:08.004
outcome data on these tumors. And so we could then ask, "Are any of these

413
00:25:08.044 --> 00:25:10.944
mutations associated with poor metastatic outcome?"

414
00:25:11.764 --> 00:25:15.444
And indeed, many were. Loss-of-function mutations affecting SwitchSNF,

415
00:25:16.264 --> 00:25:19.844
gain-of-function mutations in the MAP kinase signaling cascade, and

416
00:25:19.904 --> 00:25:22.964
loss-of-function mutations in the TGF-beta signaling cascade.

417
00:25:23.584 --> 00:25:26.524
These were all associated with poor metastatic outcome.

418
00:25:27.444 --> 00:25:30.224
Now, in addition to whole exome sequencing, we also performed the largest

419
00:25:30.304 --> 00:25:34.004
transcriptomic analysis of cutaneous squamous cell carcinomas, and after

420
00:25:34.064 --> 00:25:35.184
consensus clustering,

421
00:25:36.064 --> 00:25:39.403
there were three sample clusters and six gene expression clusters.

422
00:25:40.124 --> 00:25:44.104
It was encouraging that the sample clusters did correlate with

423
00:25:44.164 --> 00:25:47.904
outcome, one with poor outcome, one with favorable outcome, and one with

424
00:25:47.984 --> 00:25:51.764
intermediate outcome. And when you ask what is driving this clustering,

425
00:25:52.544 --> 00:25:56.244
there's a few different signals, but the main signal is the differentiation

426
00:25:56.324 --> 00:26:00.084
status of the keratinocytes. As a secondary signal, there was a

427
00:26:00.224 --> 00:26:01.664
change in metabolism.

428
00:26:02.564 --> 00:26:06.424
The favorable outcome tumors relied on lipid oxidation, whereas the poor outcome

429
00:26:06.524 --> 00:26:09.404
tumors were more likely to rely on glycolysis.

430
00:26:10.124 --> 00:26:12.294
We were somewhat surprised that we didn't see an immune signal.

431
00:26:13.024 --> 00:26:16.974
Now, if you look at individual tumors, there are definitely differences

432
00:26:17.004 --> 00:26:20.634
in the states of immune cells, but it did not

433
00:26:20.664 --> 00:26:24.124
drive, at this higher level, the unsupervised hierarchical clustering.

434
00:26:25.284 --> 00:26:28.804
So it's encouraging that we can risk-stratify tumors

435
00:26:28.844 --> 00:26:32.804
with this thousand genes, but that's an unwieldy signature

436
00:26:32.864 --> 00:26:34.824
if your goal was to bring this into the clinic.

437
00:26:35.504 --> 00:26:39.184
And so we distilled the signature down into a simplified version of

438
00:26:39.364 --> 00:26:43.244
23 genes using a Cox net model, and you can see the list of the 23

439
00:26:43.324 --> 00:26:43.864
genes here.

440
00:26:44.744 --> 00:26:48.204
Generally speaking, these genes are involved in keratinocyte

441
00:26:48.284 --> 00:26:51.854
differentiation, which is not necessarily surprising because this was the strongest

442
00:26:51.884 --> 00:26:55.504
signal observed in the unsupervised hierarchical clustering.

443
00:26:56.364 --> 00:26:59.674
But the million-dollar question is: Is this better than

444
00:26:59.724 --> 00:27:03.144
our alternatives? And the answer here is a resounding yes.

445
00:27:03.704 --> 00:27:06.824
When we compared the ability of this 23-gene expression signature

446
00:27:06.924 --> 00:27:10.773
to risk-stratify tumors in an independent validation

447
00:27:10.864 --> 00:27:14.384
cohort, that's a key detail. This is not just circular reasoning on the same

448
00:27:14.404 --> 00:27:15.164
discovery cohort.

449
00:27:16.084 --> 00:27:19.854
It dramatically outperformed Brigham and Women's and Health in the AJCC staging

450
00:27:19.924 --> 00:27:23.764
system, and even outperformed a more recent EMC

451
00:27:23.804 --> 00:27:27.784
model that was developed by my colleagues from Erasmus University

452
00:27:27.844 --> 00:27:31.264
that takes into account more clinical and histopathologic factors.

453
00:27:31.884 --> 00:27:34.144
Not only that, it works well in biopsies and excisions.

454
00:27:34.184 --> 00:27:37.664
That's always an important detail to ask for these gene expression predictors

455
00:27:37.704 --> 00:27:41.664
because you don't want a gene expression predictor that is tied to

456
00:27:41.704 --> 00:27:44.304
surgical procedure or microdissection technique.

457
00:27:45.504 --> 00:27:48.884
So in conclusion, we performed whole exome and RNA sequencing on the largest cohort

458
00:27:48.924 --> 00:27:51.544
to date of cutaneous squamous cell carcinomas linked to outcome.

459
00:27:52.124 --> 00:27:55.964
I said there was no TCGA project for this cancer, so we're hoping that this

460
00:27:56.024 --> 00:27:59.324
will effectively serve as that TCGA project that never happened.

461
00:28:00.184 --> 00:28:04.144
We cataloged the driver mutations and found that there are some that

462
00:28:04.664 --> 00:28:05.964
correlate with poor prognosis.

463
00:28:06.944 --> 00:28:10.053
We also performed transcriptomic analyses showing that

464
00:28:10.744 --> 00:28:14.694
tumors with poor differentiation gene expression signatures have

465
00:28:14.964 --> 00:28:18.684
poor metastatic outcome, and this is captured quite well with a 23-gene

466
00:28:18.744 --> 00:28:22.144
expression signature that outperforms common staging systems.

467
00:28:23.024 --> 00:28:26.964
As part of H-Stand, we're now layering on additional omic assays, including spatial

468
00:28:27.004 --> 00:28:30.624
transcriptomics, hoping that we can find yet even more biomarkers within this rich

469
00:28:30.704 --> 00:28:31.264
data set.

470
00:28:32.344 --> 00:28:36.104
So with that, I'd like to acknowledge everyone that made this work possible,

471
00:28:37.064 --> 00:28:40.344
particularly Barbara Renteria-Pacheco, the trainee from

472
00:28:40.704 --> 00:28:44.124
Erasmus University, who led these studies, as well as my

473
00:28:44.424 --> 00:28:48.084
European colleagues, Luz Holestein, Marlies Swakhuis, and Domenico Bellomo.

474
00:28:48.473 --> 00:28:50.444
And then for the earlier work

475
00:28:52.304 --> 00:28:55.204
on normal keratinocytes, Vishal Tandekar and Delaney Diveltern.

476
00:28:56.384 --> 00:29:00.364
So with that, we have time for questions if there are any, and if

477
00:29:00.404 --> 00:29:02.644
you do have a question, please come up to one of these mics.

478
00:29:13.124 --> 00:29:14.244
Could you explain the

479
00:29:15.244 --> 00:29:19.164
mutational phenotype a little better and whether or not it could apply

480
00:29:19.204 --> 00:29:22.884
to many other situations, particularly the MSI high

481
00:29:22.964 --> 00:29:26.044
phenotype where the MSI is acquired

482
00:29:27.184 --> 00:29:30.624
