01:03:51.310 --> 01:03:55.160
Thank you, Li. I'd like to invite our last speaker, Irene Ghobrial, who is

1060
01:03:56.750 --> 01:04:00.340
PI of the Multiple Myeloma Precancer Atlas from

1061
01:04:00.370 --> 01:04:01.830
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.

1062
01:04:05.250 --> 01:04:09.180
All right. Thank you. I'd like to thank, of course, AACR for this wonderful

1063
01:04:09.290 --> 01:04:12.990
time and, above all, NCI and H10, because this has been

1064
01:04:13.050 --> 01:04:17.000
really a wonderful collaboration between all of the H10 members, and we've

1065
01:04:17.010 --> 01:04:19.830
been learning a lot from all of the different cancers.

1066
01:04:19.870 --> 01:04:23.170
So I'll take you through our multiple myeloma atlas and really

1067
01:04:23.210 --> 01:04:27.150
understanding the transition from precancerous MGUS

1068
01:04:27.170 --> 01:04:30.270
and smoldering myeloma to overt myeloma and how we can prevent it.

1069
01:04:30.970 --> 01:04:32.429
These are my conflicts of interest.

1070
01:04:34.570 --> 01:04:38.050
So if you think about multiple myeloma, it has two

1071
01:04:38.130 --> 01:04:40.750
well-known transitions of precursor conditions.

1072
01:04:40.870 --> 01:04:44.830
One is called MGUS, monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance, and the

1073
01:04:44.870 --> 01:04:48.670
other one is smoldering myeloma. And they're very different because MGUS is

1074
01:04:48.750 --> 01:04:50.519
very common in the general population.

1075
01:04:50.550 --> 01:04:54.420
Anyone over the age of 50, it's about 3% to 5% of us walking around

1076
01:04:54.450 --> 01:04:57.830
with it, and it increases more and more as we get older.

1077
01:04:57.930 --> 01:05:01.000
Smoldering myeloma, which is defined by having

1078
01:05:01.030 --> 01:05:04.990
10% plasma cells or cancer cells in your bone marrow, is the

1079
01:05:05.030 --> 01:05:08.600
next transition of that. And in these patients,

1080
01:05:08.990 --> 01:05:12.910
their chance of progression to overt myeloma to end organ damage is much

1081
01:05:12.930 --> 01:05:16.550
higher. So instead of being only 1% per year, now

1082
01:05:16.690 --> 01:05:19.370
it's 10% per year, so 10 times higher.

1083
01:05:19.790 --> 01:05:22.790
And in some of those patients, when we see them, they have something called

1084
01:05:22.930 --> 01:05:26.790
high-risk smoldering myeloma, meaning that they will go on to develop

1085
01:05:26.870 --> 01:05:30.700
end organ damage or overt myeloma, 50% chance in two

1086
01:05:30.750 --> 01:05:34.650
years. So when I sit down with a patient and I see them and I tell them,

1087
01:05:34.710 --> 01:05:38.390
"You have high-risk smoldering myeloma," I'm basically telling them, "You have a

1088
01:05:38.670 --> 01:05:42.660
50/50 chance of getting fractures in your bones, kidney failure,

1089
01:05:42.660 --> 01:05:46.529
anemia in the next two years." And yet we do nothing about it.

1090
01:05:47.130 --> 01:05:51.050
So we had a question, and part of the H10 was this: Can we be

1091
01:05:51.150 --> 01:05:54.510
more precise in our definition of who is high risk in the

1092
01:05:54.630 --> 01:05:58.170
population, and who are those patients who we should be treating early,

1093
01:05:58.530 --> 01:06:02.050
while others who may never progress in their lifetime, we should leave them alone?

1094
01:06:02.490 --> 01:06:06.110
And currently, the markers that we use are basically very clinical

1095
01:06:06.190 --> 01:06:10.050
markers. How much tumor burden you have, how many plasma cells you have in

1096
01:06:10.130 --> 01:06:13.970
your bone marrow, are they 20%? How much M spike you have, which is the

1097
01:06:13.990 --> 01:06:16.880
protein we secrete in the blood or light chains.

1098
01:06:17.230 --> 01:06:19.630
And these are really only tumor burden markers.

1099
01:06:19.670 --> 01:06:21.490
They don't tell you anything about the biology.

1100
01:06:21.520 --> 01:06:24.750
They don't tell you anything about the immune system or genomic alterations.

1101
01:06:26.190 --> 01:06:29.850
So we asked the question, should we really intervene in those patients

1102
01:06:29.930 --> 01:06:33.690
early? And we're trying to look basically like the solid tumor people, like breast

1103
01:06:33.770 --> 01:06:36.040
cancer. In breast cancer, we screen early

1104
01:06:36.890 --> 01:06:39.690
and we use mammography or colonoscopy in colon cancer.

1105
01:06:39.710 --> 01:06:43.630
Yet I can tell you in multiple myeloma, a blood disease, we can

1106
01:06:43.690 --> 01:06:47.570
use a very simple blood test called serum protein electrophoresis, and it's

1107
01:06:47.610 --> 01:06:50.910
much easier to screen by a blood test than doing mammography or

1108
01:06:50.970 --> 01:06:54.950
colonoscopy. And even when we find those patients with high-risk

1109
01:06:55.070 --> 01:06:58.820
smoldering myeloma, which is very much like a malignancy, like a Stage 1 or

1110
01:06:58.910 --> 01:07:02.270
Stage 2 breast cancer, we tell our patients, "Watch and wait.

1111
01:07:02.590 --> 01:07:06.310
Do nothing until you have metastasis everywhere, basically." Just like metastatic

1112
01:07:06.370 --> 01:07:10.350
breast cancer. Wait until you have fractures, bone disease,

1113
01:07:10.390 --> 01:07:13.310
or kidney failure, and then I treat you. And that's a problem.

1114
01:07:13.350 --> 01:07:16.780
That's basically saying to a patient with multiple myeloma, "Wait until you have

1115
01:07:16.830 --> 01:07:20.680
advanced disease, and then I treat you." So the way we were thinking of this

1116
01:07:20.730 --> 01:07:24.180
is can we diagnose those patients early and potentially treat them

1117
01:07:24.230 --> 01:07:27.350
early and shift the way of thinking into an early

1118
01:07:27.390 --> 01:07:31.306
interception?To do that, you need to be more precise

1119
01:07:31.346 --> 01:07:34.426
in your risk stratification. So I'll show you some of the work that we've been

1120
01:07:34.466 --> 01:07:37.166
doing with our H10 collaboration here.

1121
01:07:37.186 --> 01:07:40.706
And the first one was trying to understand the genomic alterations that can be

1122
01:07:40.746 --> 01:07:42.986
predictive of progression in our patients.

1123
01:07:43.446 --> 01:07:47.136
So here we took 218 patients with MGUS and smoldering

1124
01:07:47.206 --> 01:07:50.826
myeloma and compared it to patients who have already gone to overt

1125
01:07:50.866 --> 01:07:53.656
multiple myeloma, and we did whole genome sequencing.

1126
01:07:53.926 --> 01:07:57.716
And this is hard to do from peripheral blood or bone marrow cells, especially when

1127
01:07:57.726 --> 01:07:59.186
you have very small numbers of cells.

1128
01:07:59.626 --> 01:08:03.046
But we were able to find those alterations, and then we put them on a scale.

1129
01:08:03.146 --> 01:08:07.096
We wanted to make this something that's clinically relevant for our patients, so I

1130
01:08:07.126 --> 01:08:11.106
can tomorrow go to the clinic and tell them, "Here is your genomic score." And

1131
01:08:11.146 --> 01:08:14.936
we call that the MM-like score. And it's a simple score of how

1132
01:08:14.966 --> 01:08:18.566
many you have that are more MGUS-like, which is only 14, 16, or

1133
01:08:18.626 --> 01:08:22.257
14, 20, and how many are myeloma-like, which, as you see here,

1134
01:08:22.427 --> 01:08:25.826
NRAS, KRAS, 1q amplification, MYC alterations, and so on.

1135
01:08:26.266 --> 01:08:29.587
And you balance them, and if you have more of the one, then you're more

1136
01:08:29.606 --> 01:08:32.946
myeloma-like, and if you have more of the MGUS-like, then you're actually

1137
01:08:33.106 --> 01:08:36.186
MGUS-like, even if you have a high tumor burden.

1138
01:08:36.206 --> 01:08:39.346
And that's a critical one that we can now use in the clinic.

1139
01:08:40.286 --> 01:08:43.996
But we said, "Well, that's not really using single-cell level information, and

1140
01:08:44.026 --> 01:08:47.616
that's also not looking at the transcriptional changes that occur in the patients."

1141
01:08:47.967 --> 01:08:51.726
We know that many patients may have a 14, 16, or a 1q amplification,

1142
01:08:52.047 --> 01:08:54.166
and yet they don't progress to multiple myeloma.

1143
01:08:54.486 --> 01:08:57.826
There is something more beyond the genomic alterations of those patients.

1144
01:08:58.257 --> 01:09:02.126
So we decided to do single-cell sequencing with BCR sequencing

1145
01:09:02.186 --> 01:09:05.686
so that we can truly look at the malignant plasma cells versus the normal plasma

1146
01:09:05.706 --> 01:09:08.346
cells. And here we looked at 1.7 million

1147
01:09:09.146 --> 01:09:13.126
cells from 226 patients. And this was a collaboration with

1148
01:09:13.206 --> 01:09:16.525
Gary Guss at the Broad Institute, where we tried to ask the question

1149
01:09:16.566 --> 01:09:19.116
transcriptionally, what's happening in those patients?

1150
01:09:19.427 --> 01:09:22.976
But because those are the same patients, we also did whole-genome sequencing.

1151
01:09:23.007 --> 01:09:26.786
Another question was, what can you define beyond the DNA level and

1152
01:09:26.806 --> 01:09:28.146
beyond genomic alterations?

1153
01:09:29.366 --> 01:09:33.306
Now, this was a hard thing to do because we're now comparing tumor to tumor, but

1154
01:09:33.387 --> 01:09:37.087
also bone marrow plasma cells versus peripheral blood circulating tumor

1155
01:09:37.186 --> 01:09:40.427
cells, and we're also looking at normal cells versus normal cells.

1156
01:09:40.726 --> 01:09:42.746
And you can ask a lot of the questions here.

1157
01:09:43.306 --> 01:09:46.927
The first one we wanted to do is, can we look at those transcriptional

1158
01:09:47.007 --> 01:09:50.666
changes that occur during transition from a normal plasma

1159
01:09:50.766 --> 01:09:54.746
cell to an MGUS cell to a more malignant transformed smoldering

1160
01:09:54.786 --> 01:09:58.346
myeloma or myeloma cell. And you can see that we found 16

1161
01:09:58.366 --> 01:10:02.066
transcriptional signatures that were defined in those populations,

1162
01:10:02.106 --> 01:10:05.466
including cell cycle regulation, as you probably expect,

1163
01:10:05.866 --> 01:10:09.426
MHC Class II, checkpoint regulation, and so on,

1164
01:10:09.526 --> 01:10:13.126
circulatory capacity. But then we took those and went and tried to

1165
01:10:13.186 --> 01:10:16.926
see which ones truly predict for you progression to multiple myeloma.

1166
01:10:17.315 --> 01:10:21.186
And we found that six of those signatures were very critical for that

1167
01:10:21.206 --> 01:10:24.936
progression from MGUS to smoldering myeloma to overt myeloma.

1168
01:10:25.456 --> 01:10:29.136
And this is very critical, especially beta-2M, which is in the MHC Class

1169
01:10:29.346 --> 01:10:33.246
I. And you can tell that this is critical because we use beta-2M as one

1170
01:10:33.266 --> 01:10:36.966
of our predictors of progression in our patients, and the ISS

1171
01:10:37.046 --> 01:10:39.346
classification of multiple myeloma.

1172
01:10:40.606 --> 01:10:43.246
Now, we further validated that in the COMPASS data.

1173
01:10:43.286 --> 01:10:47.056
This is a larger data set that has overt multiple myeloma from

1174
01:10:47.146 --> 01:10:50.886
MMRF, and we indeed found that in the same signatures were

1175
01:10:50.926 --> 01:10:53.226
found even if you have overt multiple myeloma.

1176
01:10:53.286 --> 01:10:57.006
So this is not just the precursor conditions, but can also be applied in

1177
01:10:57.046 --> 01:11:00.086
patients with overt myeloma, even when they receive therapy.

1178
01:11:01.266 --> 01:11:04.886
Now, the next question we said is, well, that's good enough to have signatures, but

1179
01:11:04.926 --> 01:11:08.875
let's try to find a classifier that can predict for me, if I take a patient with

1180
01:11:08.906 --> 01:11:12.815
smoldering myeloma and I looked at their cells, I can tell where they

1181
01:11:12.886 --> 01:11:16.806
are in their transition from normal to MGUS to smoldering to myeloma

1182
01:11:16.866 --> 01:11:20.586
because the way that we classify our patients clinically may actually be wrong.

1183
01:11:20.886 --> 01:11:24.666
I may be classifying some patients who have MGUS that truly have more smoldering

1184
01:11:24.706 --> 01:11:28.506
myeloma in their transcriptional biological changes and vice versa.

1185
01:11:28.576 --> 01:11:32.526
A patient with 10% plasma cells, so I call them smoldering myeloma, but

1186
01:11:32.566 --> 01:11:35.226
they will never progress. They're behaving more like MGUS.

1187
01:11:35.626 --> 01:11:39.566
So can I take your cell and by single-cell signatures, tell

1188
01:11:39.626 --> 01:11:43.546
you where you stand in that transition period, and can I put it

1189
01:11:43.606 --> 01:11:45.306
in the axis of progression?

1190
01:11:46.246 --> 01:11:50.225
So here what we did is we tried to do a malignancy score and a disease score.

1191
01:11:50.546 --> 01:11:54.376
Malignancy score just tells me, are you normal or a malignant plasma cell?

1192
01:11:54.526 --> 01:11:58.346
And with 100% accuracy, we can tell at the single-cell level if this is a

1193
01:11:58.406 --> 01:12:00.486
normal plasma cell or a malignant plasma cell.

1194
01:12:00.886 --> 01:12:04.746
Then the next question is, what is the malignancy score as a

1195
01:12:04.806 --> 01:12:07.626
disease progression from MGUS to smoldering to myeloma?

1196
01:12:08.016 --> 01:12:11.966
And here we actually classified it from the MGUS and myeloma samples and then came

1197
01:12:12.046 --> 01:12:14.306
back and looked at it in the smoldering samples.

1198
01:12:14.686 --> 01:12:18.576
And we indeed found that you can create a score, we called it the MST score, that

1199
01:12:18.606 --> 01:12:22.326
can predict for you progression, and it correlates, of course, with disease burden,

1200
01:12:22.406 --> 01:12:25.886
with the light chain, with the M spike, but it can actually predict for you

1201
01:12:25.926 --> 01:12:29.666
progression, not only in the MGUS and smoldering myeloma and myeloma

1202
01:12:29.766 --> 01:12:33.746
patients, but also again in the COMPASS database, which is the overt myeloma

1203
01:12:33.786 --> 01:12:37.566
patients. And that classifier is critical for us because again,

1204
01:12:37.646 --> 01:12:41.626
beyond the DNA data, we can use it now in the clinic as a

1205
01:12:41.646 --> 01:12:45.346
classifier to tell us at the transcriptional level what's happening to the patient.

1206
01:12:46.086 --> 01:12:50.026
Now, the next question we asked is, can it add anything more beyond the DNA

1207
01:12:50.066 --> 01:12:53.986
level? I already know that my patients have genomic signatures, which is

1208
01:12:54.026 --> 01:12:57.986
the MM-like score. Should I add on it the RNA data, or is

1209
01:12:58.046 --> 01:13:00.526
just reflecting what happened at the DNA level?

1210
01:13:00.926 --> 01:13:04.806
And here what we did is we actually removed the DNA information because

1211
01:13:04.846 --> 01:13:08.826
we found very weak correlation between RNA and DNA from the same patients, and we

1212
01:13:08.866 --> 01:13:12.786
went back and said, "What is the transcriptional change that is occurring above

1213
01:13:12.806 --> 01:13:16.686
and beyond what you have at the genomic level from the DNA mutations?" And

1214
01:13:16.726 --> 01:13:20.586
you can find that the circulatory capacity, the ability of the cells to circulate

1215
01:13:20.606 --> 01:13:24.446
in the peripheral blood, as well as histone chaperone proteins and genes, were

1216
01:13:24.506 --> 01:13:28.466
critical for that transition, which tells you that there is a lot of work

1217
01:13:28.486 --> 01:13:32.446
to be done beyond the DNA level to really tell us why those cells become

1218
01:13:32.486 --> 01:13:35.606
more malignant, even in the early MGUS stages in our

1219
01:13:35.646 --> 01:13:39.282
patients.Because circulatory capacity and because the

1220
01:13:39.362 --> 01:13:43.302
CTCs, or circulating tumor cells, are so prognostic in our patients, and

1221
01:13:43.342 --> 01:13:47.302
we know that by flow cytometry, we went back and said, "Then let's do a larger

1222
01:13:47.342 --> 01:13:51.002
cohort of single-cell sequencing in the peripheral blood so that we can really

1223
01:13:51.042 --> 01:13:54.582
define what's happening in the bone marrow, but only in the peripheral blood." Can

1224
01:13:54.722 --> 01:13:58.442
I just use a blood sample from you and tell you if you have the

1225
01:13:58.502 --> 01:14:00.822
genomic alterations that are in the bone marrow?

1226
01:14:00.842 --> 01:14:04.802
And potentially, we can also stop doing bone marrow biopsies in

1227
01:14:04.842 --> 01:14:08.422
our patients because they're very hard to do, and patients don't like to do it.

1228
01:14:08.842 --> 01:14:12.522
So here, this is work that we did from 74 patients and 29 healthy

1229
01:14:12.762 --> 01:14:16.562
